4-27-85 This is just an awesome show with great Charlie Miller sound. Jerry was so strung out in '85 you never knew what you were going to get but he brought his A game to this show!

There seems to be a beat now..I can feel it in my feet now Great sound to this one..You can feel the electricity through the music..Sparking on all cylinders!! I love the son selection from start to finish..The Ramble on Rose is ever so nice in the 1st set..I will also mention the killer Scarlet>Eyes>GDTFB>Woman R Smarter to start a sweet 2nd set>> Yeah Boy..Also a nice The Wheel out of space and a haunting Black Peter..so please>GIVE IT A WHIRL!!! Forever Grateful>Forever Dead@!@!@!@!

A chance for folks to meet.. I had this 1st set and really enjoyed listening to it especially in 85
The thing was -this was the Grateful Dead I was going to see.
I loved all my classic tapes but this was right in front of me.

I listened to this entire show before sitting down to review it 
and I got to say this show stands the test of time.

Dancin>Bertha to start and Rain &Snow>MUSIC to close.
A great Tom Thumbs!
2nd Set Scarlet >Eyes>GDTRFB
and Weir gets a Truckin>TOO and a Around >Saturday Night
This is a loose , well played ,outside the box show
also probably proof that a DAY JOB encore
was not an indication of anything in particular.
You might want a ballad encore for your sweetheart
but the DAY JOB had some rocking balls to it.

1985 Slapper I hadn’t listened to this show in many, many years but decided to give it a spin when I heard Dave picked it for commercial release. The Dancin’ opener immediately brought me back to that fun day at Frost. Yes, Jerry’s vocals are strained but his playing, well, that was sharp indeed, and the rest of the band responded in kind. Check out the Jerry triple play to start the second set, for example, and the transition from Scarlet to Eyes. The leads are bright and shiny and the music is stitched into a syncopated, beautiful, layered mosaic. Simply, this is as good as it gets for 1985, and a fine time capsule of the band from that year for archival preservation. Nice call Dave, and thanks for the reminder that, on any given day, the GD could still deliver the goods, at an idyllic venue with perfect sound, even 20 years into their long strange trip.
